\paragraph{Local bidirectionality benefits structured representations.}
The results in the left block of Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide} reveal a distinct advantage for non-causal modeling.
While performance on standard physics problems (Phys) remains comparable, \textsc{SDAR} unlocks massive gains on \textbf{ChemBench (+12.3\%)} and the expert-level \textbf{GPQA-diamond (+5.5\%)}.
We attribute this to the diffusion mechanism's ability to refine complex tokens (such as chemical formulas) simultaneously within a block. This allows the model to capture local dependencies that a left-to-right scan might miss or struggle to cohere, effectively bypassing the causal bottleneck inherent to AR processing of non-linguistic data.
\paragraph{Sequential logic is preserved.}
As shown in the right block of Table~\ref{tab:combined_results_wide}, this specialized advantage does not come at the cost of general capability.
\textsc{SDAR} demonstrates remarkable stability on logic-heavy benchmarks (MMLU-P, AIME), and notably outperforms AR on difficult tasks like LiveMathBench-Hard (+5.3\%) and LiveCodeBench-v6 (+5.1\%).
This validates that the paradigm shift changes \textit{how} the model generates text—enhancing its handling of local structures—without disrupting the global causal chain-of-thought logic internalized during pretraining.
\subsection{Diversity and Test-Time Scaling}
\label{ssec:test_time_scaling}
Finally, we examine how the stochastic nature of diffusion-based sampling interacts with test-time scaling strategies. Unlike AR sampling which relies solely on top-$k$/$p$ truncation, diffusion introduces noise at every denoising step, potentially generating more diverse valid trajectories.
Table~\ref{tab:ar_vs_sdar_delta_transposed_subset} details performance under Majority Voting and Pass@k ($k=32$) protocols.
\paragraph{Diffusion noise maximizes ensemble efficiency.}
\textsc{SDAR} exhibits exceptional synergy with scaling strategies.
While single-sample performance is comparable to AR, applying majority voting yields massive gains: \textbf{+19.3\% on AIME-2025} and \textbf{+15.7\% on LiveMathBench-hard}.
Furthermore, Pass@k metrics reach 93.3\% on AIME-2024 and 87.5\% on LMB-hard.
This suggests that the non-causal generation process produces a higher diversity of correct reasoning paths ("System 2" thinking). Consequently, \textsc{SDAR} serves as a highly effective generator for ensemble-based inference, converting compute time into accuracy more efficiently than standard AR sampling.
